{
  "text": "The term \"apoptotic bodies\" was coined by Kerr in 1972 [CITATION_1] . They are membrane vesicles released into the extracellular environment when cells are undergoing apoptosis during the last stages of cell death [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The major difference between ABs and other cell-derived vesicles is their size because they are 1-5 m in diameter [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Moreover, they are heterogeneous in shape [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] and present intact organelles, histones and genomic DNA within the vesicles [CITATION_9] . In general, ABs are released by membrane blebbing that requires phosphorylation of myosin light chain and the activation of caspase-3, one of the key enzymes of apoptosis [CITATION_10] .",
